&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;August 29, 2024 – December 21, 2024.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Note: Some of the formatting might have been lost when migrating this page.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;img src=&#34;https://res.cloudinary.com/dwwbmrctk/image/upload/q_auto/f_auto/v1782070565/7A22032B-56DA-4EDF-8350-BA850B5C21B7_ly1mln.jpg&#34; width=&#34;600&#34; height=&#34;600&#34; alt=&#34;Pop Loser Vol. 3&#34;&gt;
&lt;!-- end-chunk --&gt;
&lt;!-- begin-chunk data-anchor=&#34;heading&#34; --&gt;

&lt;h3 class=&#34;header-anchor-wrapper&#34;&gt;&lt;i class=&#34;fa-solid fa-skull-crossbones&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;i class=&#34;fa-solid fa-skull-crossbones&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;i class=&#34;fa-solid fa-skull-crossbones&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;
  &lt;a href=&#34;#heading&#34; class=&#34;header-anchor-link&#34;&gt;
&lt;svg
    xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/2000/svg&#34;
    width=&#34;1rem&#34; height=&#34;1rem&#34; viewBox=&#34;0 0 24 24&#34; fill=&#34;none&#34;
    stroke=&#34;currentColor&#34; stroke-width=&#34;2&#34; stroke-linecap=&#34;round&#34;
    stroke-linejoin=&#34;round&#34;&gt;
    &lt;line x1=&#34;4&#34; y1=&#34;9&#34; x2=&#34;20&#34; y2=&#34;9&#34;&gt;&lt;/line&gt;&lt;line x1=&#34;4&#34; y1=&#34;15&#34; x2=&#34;20&#34; y2=&#34;15&#34;&gt;&lt;/line&gt;&lt;line x1=&#34;10&#34; y1=&#34;3&#34; x2=&#34;8&#34; y2=&#34;21&#34;&gt;&lt;/line&gt;&lt;line x1=&#34;16&#34; y1=&#34;3&#34; x2=&#34;14&#34; y2=&#34;21&#34;&gt;&lt;/line&gt;
&lt;/svg&gt;

&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I used to know how computers work. If something broke, either inside my laptop or on my website, I could usually figure it out and fix it. It was a thing I enjoyed doing. Somewhere along the way, I stopped knowing how things work and stopped wanting to figure it out. Part of that is that I bought a bunch of products and started using websites that &amp;ldquo;just work.&amp;rdquo; Part of it was just me getting older and devoting more of that time to things like learning to make bread, reading books and having a few time-sucking kids. It happens.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Last winter, the arcade cabinet I built a couple years ago crapped out. Screen went black and it wouldn&amp;rsquo;t turn on. I poked at it for about 10 minutes and then walked away, because trying to relearn how I made it work in the first place was too daunting, never mind troubleshooting software and hardware in a rigorous way. Too hard! Too much!
One of the time-sucking children finally complained — he had been waiting months to work on his Pac-Man score. Fair enough. The easiest solution, I figured, would be to buy the same model Raspberry Pi and just swap in the SD card and plug it in, but I didn&amp;rsquo;t know if that was possible. I found a forum, signed up and asked, getting a few pretty quick answers that amounted more or less to &amp;ldquo;Maybe&amp;hellip; but it&amp;rsquo;s probably not that simple.&amp;rdquo; Then one guy suggested I replace the power supply — an $8 plug — because reasons (the specifics don&amp;rsquo;t matter here, but I assure you every response I got was fucking &lt;em&gt;thorough&lt;/em&gt;. Sure enough, that&amp;rsquo;s all it was and boy did I feel stupid and lazy. Don&amp;rsquo;t tell my kids.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I hope you enjoyed your summer. Welcome to Pop Loser Vol. 3.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;!-- end-chunk --&gt;
&lt;!-- begin-chunk data-anchor=&#34;heading-1&#34; --&gt;

&lt;h3 class=&#34;header-anchor-wrapper&#34;&gt;&lt;i class=&#34;fa-solid fa-skull-crossbones&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;i class=&#34;fa-solid fa-skull-crossbones&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;i class=&#34;fa-solid fa-skull-crossbones&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;
